    <h1>WILDLIFE PARTS AND PROD&#xAD;UCTS</h1>
    <h2>Last year, Na&#xAD;tional Parks Board seized</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200825/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-25"><time>2020-08-25</time></a>
        - <span>HOME</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>37.5 tonnes of pan­golin scales</p>
    <p>Pan­golin scales</p>
    <p>The pan­golin is one of the most traf­ficked an­i­mals glob­ally and some claim the scales have medic­i­nal prop­er­ties, de­spite a lack of ev­i­dence to sug­gest so. Some species are crit­i­cally en­dan­gered, while other species are listed as vul­ner­a­ble.</p>
    <p>9 tonnes of ivory and ivory prod­ucts</p>
    <p>Ivory</p>
    <p>The global ivory trade is a key wildlife con­ser­va­tion is­sue be­cause of dwin­dling ele­phant pop­u­la­tions. Sin­ga­pore’s ban on the do­mes­tic trade of ivory will come into ef­fect on Sept 1 next year.</p>
    <p>638 wildlife parts and prod­ucts</p>
    <p>Marine tur­tle eggs</p>
    <p>The eggs are some­times eaten as a del­i­cacy or for tra­di­tional medicine pur­poses, but the an­i­mals are listed as en­dan­gered.</p>
    <p>Snake wines</p>
    <p>Snake wine is touted to cure ev­ery­thing from hair loss to im­prov­ing sex­ual prow­ess. How­ever, snakes used for its pro­duc­tion may be en­dan­gered.</p>
    <p>Hard coral</p>
    <p>Corals are har­vested for sou­venirs, marine aquar­i­ums or for med­i­cal use, but the in­dis­crim­i­nate har­vest­ing de­stroys reefs.</p>

